      "Synthetic 31-amino-acid peptide analog of native human GLP-1 (glucagon-like peptide-1), engineered for substantially extended half-life via two structural modifications: (1) substitution of alanine at position 8 with α-aminoisobutyric acid (Aib) to resist DPP-4 (dipeptidyl peptidase-4) degradation, and (2) attachment of a C18 fatty diacid chain via a γGlu-2xOEG linker to enable albumin binding. The net result is a half-life of ~7 days vs native GLP-1's ~2 minutes — enabling weekly subcutaneous dosing. **Mechanism — GLP-1 receptor agonism (the central effect)**: semaglutide is a selective agonist at the GLP-1 receptor (GLP-1R), a class B G-protein-coupled receptor expressed on pancreatic β-cells, α-cells, gastric and small intestinal smooth muscle, vagal afferent neurons, hypothalamic and brainstem nuclei (including arcuate nucleus, area postrema, nucleus tractus solitarius), cardiovascular tissue, and adipose tissue. **Mechanism — pancreatic effects**: glucose-dependent insulin secretion (β-cell stimulation only when glucose is elevated, which is the design feature that prevents fasting hypoglycemia); suppression of glucagon secretion from α-cells; preservation of β-cell function with possible neogenesis effects in long-term use. The glucose-dependence of insulin response is the central reason GLP-1 RAs do not cause hypoglycemia as monotherapy. **Mechanism — gastric emptying delay**: substantial slowing of gastric emptying via vagal pathways, contributing to postprandial glucose attenuation and prolonged satiety. The gastric emptying effect is the principal mechanism behind both meal-related GI side effects (nausea, vomiting, fullness) and the meal-volume reduction that drives weight loss. **Mechanism — central appetite regulation**: GLP-1R activation in the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus and brainstem nuclei drives anorectic effects via POMC/CART neuron activation and AgRP/NPY neuron suppression. The central appetite suppression is the dominant mechanism behind sustained weight loss — distinct from the gastric emptying contribution which attenuates over time as tachyphylaxis develops to GI effects. **Mechanism — cardiovascular effects**: GLP-1R activation in vascular endothelium, cardiomyocytes, and atherosclerotic plaque produces measurable effects on endothelial function, blood pressure, heart rate (mild increase), and inflammatory markers. The cardiovascular effects translate to clinical outcome benefits established in dedicated CVOT trials. **Pharmaceutical formulations**: Ozempic (T2D, weekly SubQ pen, 0.25-2.0mg dose range), Wegovy (chronic weight management, weekly SubQ pen, 0.25-2.4mg dose range with 16-week titration), Rybelsus (T2D, daily oral 3-14mg with strict empty-stomach administration protocol — must be taken with ≤120mL water, 30 minutes before food/fluids/other oral medications; oral bioavailability is achieved via co-formulation with the absorption enhancer SNAC). **Pharmacokinetics**: half-life ~7 days; steady state at 4-5 weeks; titration over 16 weeks for Wegovy to mitigate GI tolerability. SubQ Ozempic/Wegovy: weekly dosing flexibility — same day each week, no specific time required. Oral Rybelsus: daily dosing with the empty-stomach protocol non-negotiable for absorption.",
