    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Modern Incretin Era\n\nSemaglutide is the molecule that established modern GLP-1 receptor agonist therapy as a mainstream pharmacotherapy class for both type 2 diabetes and obesity. The SUSTAIN trial program (T2D) and STEP trial program (obesity) generated the clinical evidence base; SELECT 2023 established cardiovascular outcome benefits in overweight/obesity even without diabetes. The FLOW trial (2024) added renal outcome benefits in T2D with CKD.\n\nTirzepatide (the dual GIP/GLP-1 agonist covered separately in this catalog) has since shown greater weight loss than semaglutide in head-to-head SURMOUNT-5 trial data, but semaglutide retains the broadest evidence base across indications and the broadest pharmaceutical formulation portfolio (SubQ + oral routes).\n\n## Three Pharmaceutical Formulations\n\n### Ozempic (SubQ, T2D)\n- Pre-filled multi-dose pen\n- Doses: 0.25, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0mg weekly\n- Titration: 4 weeks at 0.25mg, then 0.5mg standard maintenance, escalate to 1.0mg or 2.0mg as needed\n- T2D indication; commonly used off-label for weight management\n\n### Wegovy (SubQ, obesity / chronic weight management)\n- Pre-filled multi-dose pen\n- Doses: 0.25, 0.5, 1.0, 1.7, 2.4mg weekly\n- 16-week titration to 2.4mg maintenance is the labeled protocol\n- Indicated for adults with BMI ≥30, or ≥27 with weight-related comorbidity; also approved for adolescents 12+ with obesity\n\n### Rybelsus (oral, T2D)\n- Oral tablet\n- Doses: 3, 7, 14mg daily\n- **Strict empty-stomach protocol** — must be taken with ≤120mL water, ≥30 minutes before food/fluids/other oral medications; absorption substantially impaired without protocol adherence\n- Co-formulated with SNAC (sodium N-(8-[2-hydroxybenzoyl]amino)caprylate) absorption enhancer that transiently disrupts gastric mucosal lipid bilayer to permit peptide absorption\n- Indication: T2D; not approved for obesity\n\n## Titration — The Tolerability Reality\n\nGI side effects (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, abdominal pain) are the principal user-facing tolerability issue. Faster titration produces substantially worse GI burden; the 16-week Wegovy titration is the labeled compromise between time-to-therapeutic-dose and tolerability. Strategies that improve tolerability:\n\n- **Slow titration** — staying at each dose level for 4 weeks minimum before advancing; some users benefit from 6-8 week intervals\n- **Lower meal volumes** — smaller, more frequent meals reduce postprandial nausea\n- **Avoid high-fat meals** — fat slows gastric emptying further and intensifies fullness/nausea\n- **Hydration** — counters constipation and the hypovolemia risk during GI symptom peaks\n- **Anti-nausea adjuncts** — ondansetron, ginger, B6 used clinically as needed\n- **Pause at the lowest tolerated dose** — many users can stay at 1.0mg or 1.7mg long-term with appropriate response; advancing to 2.4mg is not mandatory if lower doses provide adequate effect\n\n## Lean Mass Preservation — Critical Adjunct Consideration\n\nA substantial portion of semaglutide-induced weight loss is lean tissue rather than adipose. Mean ~30-40% of total weight loss is fat-free mass in trial cohorts without resistance training and adequate protein. This is a clinically meaningful problem — lean mass loss reduces resting metabolic rate, impairs functional capacity, and predicts weight regain.\n\nMitigation requires deliberate intervention:\n- **Protein intake 1.6-2.2g/kg target body weight** (not current weight, which overweights protein needs in obesity)\n- **Resistance training 2-4x/week** with progressive overload\n- **Adequate creatine** (3-5g/day standard supplementation)\n- Some clinical contexts add **GH-axis support** (CJC-1295, ipamorelin, tesamorelin) to preserve lean mass — outside FDA labeling but mechanistically rational\n\n## Cardiovascular Outcomes\n\n**SUSTAIN-6** (2016, NEJM): semaglutide reduced 3-point MACE in T2D with established CV disease or high risk. Established CV safety and benefit signal.\n\n**SELECT** (2023, NEJM): semaglutide 2.4mg (Wegovy dose) reduced 3-point MACE by 20% in overweight/obesity with established CV disease, without diabetes. The SELECT trial established cardiovascular benefit independent of glycemic mechanism — substantial implications for obesity pharmacotherapy as a CV intervention class.\n\n**FLOW** (2024, NEJM): semaglutide reduced major kidney outcome events in T2D with CKD. Renal protection beyond glycemic effect.\n\n**EVOKE / EVOKE+** (ongoing): semaglutide vs placebo in early Alzheimer's disease — investigating cognitive outcomes.\n\n## Synergies\n**GH-axis peptides (CJC-1295, ipamorelin, tesamorelin)** for lean mass preservation during GLP-1 weight loss. **BPC-157** for GI healing in users with semaglutide-related GI symptoms. **Comprehensive nutrition** with elevated protein and adequate fiber. **Resistance training** as the principal lean mass preservation intervention.\n\n## Anesthesia / Surgical Considerations\n\nDelayed gastric emptying creates aspiration risk during anesthesia. Pharmaceutical labeling and ASA (American Society of Anesthesiologists) guidance now recommend extended pre-procedural fasting and consideration of holding GLP-1 RAs before elective procedures. Specifics:\n- **Hold weekly SubQ formulations 1 week before elective surgery** (per ASA 2023 guidance)\n- **Hold daily oral formulations on day of surgery**\n- Disclose GLP-1 RA use to anesthesia team in all surgical and procedural contexts\n- Emergency surgery cases require aspiration precautions regardless of cessation\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nSUSTAIN program (T2D efficacy and CV outcomes — SUSTAIN-6 the foundational CVOT). STEP program (obesity efficacy — STEP-1 through STEP-8). SELECT 2023 (CV outcomes in obesity without diabetes). FLOW 2024 (renal outcomes in T2D + CKD). PIONEER program (Rybelsus oral semaglutide).\n\n## Evidence Quality\nDeepest modern incretin evidence base. FDA approvals across three indications and two routes. Cardiovascular outcome benefits established in two CVOT trials. Renal outcome benefits established. Long-term safety profile well-characterized through 5+ years of widespread clinical use. Pharmaceutical-grade formulation provides reliable potency and predictable PK.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational modern incretin evidence; multiple positive CVOT and renal outcome trials; broad FDA approval across T2D and obesity; substantial real-world evidence at population scale. Anecdote: substantial wellness-clinic and TRT-clinic prescribing practice; community familiarity with titration strategies and tolerability mitigation; lean mass preservation has emerged as the principal community concern alongside GI tolerability. Decision frame: foundational GLP-1 RA for T2D and obesity; choose pharmaceutical formulation matched to patient route preference and indication; titrate slowly for tolerability; mandatory protein and resistance training for lean mass preservation; coordinate with anesthesia for any surgical or procedural contexts.",
