    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Triple Agonist Frontier\n\nRetatrutide is the molecule that established triple receptor agonism (GLP-1 + GIP + GCG) as a viable pharmacological approach for obesity and T2D. The Phase II Jastreboff et al. NEJM 2023 publication reported the highest weight loss magnitude ever achieved in obesity pharmacotherapy — up to ~24% mean body weight reduction at 48 weeks at 12mg dose. This result substantially exceeds the ~22.5% from tirzepatide SURMOUNT-1 and ~17% from semaglutide STEP-1 at maximum doses. The Phase III TRIUMPH program is in progress; FDA approval timeline depends on trial completion and review.\n\nThe distinguishing mechanistic feature is the glucagon receptor agonism arm. Native glucagon is contraindicated as monotherapy in T2D because of hepatic glucose production effects, but balanced multi-agonism with GLP-1R and GIPR insulinotropic actions offsets the hyperglycemic risk while capturing glucagon's energy expenditure, lipid mobilization, and lipolysis benefits.\n\n## Investigational Status — The Honest Framing\n\nRetatrutide is widely used in research peptide and TRT/wellness clinic networks ahead of FDA approval. The honest framing for users considering retatrutide use:\n\n**What we know:**\n- Substantial Phase II evidence (Jastreboff 2023 NEJM and related publications)\n- Highest reported weight loss magnitude in any obesity pharmacotherapy trial\n- Phase III TRIUMPH program enrolling/in progress\n- Mechanistic case is well-established for triple-agonist metabolic effects\n- Heart rate increase is a distinctive AE requiring monitoring\n\n**What we don't yet know:**\n- Long-term safety profile (Phase III data not yet published; >2 year safety data limited)\n- Cardiovascular outcome data (no CVOT yet)\n- Renal outcome data\n- Real-world adherence and durability of effect\n- Optimal long-term dose (Phase III may extend or refine the 12mg ceiling tested in Phase II)\n\n**What pharmaceutical approval would change:**\n- Standardized formulation and reliable potency\n- Insurance coverage pathways\n- Pharmacovigilance for rare AEs\n- Standardized titration guidance and monitoring protocols\n\nUsers running retatrutide ahead of FDA approval should approach with honest acknowledgment that they are taking an investigational compound without long-term safety data, and should monitor cardiovascular markers (HR, BP), metabolic markers, and standard GLP-1 RA AE patterns appropriately.\n\n## Titration — Tolerability and Cardiovascular Monitoring\n\nTitration mitigation strategies parallel semaglutide and tirzepatide considerations (slow titration, low-volume meals, hydration, anti-nausea adjuncts). Distinctive retatrutide consideration: heart rate increase from GCGR arm warrants additional CV monitoring:\n\n- **Baseline ECG and resting HR** before initiation\n- **Resting HR check at each titration step**\n- **Re-baseline ECG if HR increases >15 bpm or any new symptoms (palpitations, chest discomfort, exercise intolerance)**\n- Users with arrhythmia history, structural heart disease, or significant CV risk should coordinate with cardiology before initiation\n\n## Dose Magnitude — The Phase II Range\n\nPhase II tested doses up to 12mg weekly. Lower doses (4-8mg) produced substantial weight loss with somewhat better tolerability. The 12mg dose produced the headline ~24% weight reduction but with greater side effect burden. Many users in research peptide community contexts achieve adequate response at 4-8mg without need to advance to maximum tested doses.\n\nPhase III TRIUMPH may test or refine higher doses; the catalog will update when Phase III data is published.\n\n## Lean Mass Preservation — Same Class Considerations\n\nLean mass loss occurs without resistance training and adequate protein, identical to semaglutide and tirzepatide considerations. Mitigation requires the same deliberate intervention:\n- Protein 1.6-2.2g/kg target body weight\n- Resistance training 2-4x/week\n- Adequate creatine\n- GH-axis support (CJC-1295, ipamorelin, tesamorelin) in some clinical contexts\n\nThe hepatic and adipose lipid mobilization effects of the GCGR arm may produce slightly more favorable adipose-vs-lean ratio than dual or single agonists; comparative body composition data is limited and pending Phase III publication.\n\n## Anesthesia / Surgical Considerations\n\nClass-effect aspiration risk per delayed gastric emptying. Hold weekly retatrutide 1 week before elective surgery per GLP-1 RA class guidance (no retatrutide-specific labeling yet). Disclose use to anesthesia team in all surgical and procedural contexts.\n\n## Synergies\nIdentical to semaglutide and tirzepatide. **GH-axis peptides** for lean mass preservation. **BPC-157** for GI healing. **Comprehensive nutrition** with elevated protein and adequate fiber. **Resistance training**. Some users combine retatrutide with cagrilintide for incretin + amylin combination effects (covered in glp3-rc tile and cagrilintide tile).\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nJastreboff et al. NEJM 2023 — Phase II obesity foundational publication. Rosenstock et al. Lancet 2023 — Phase II T2D foundational publication. TRIUMPH program (Phase III, ongoing) — multiple obesity, T2D, MASH, and CKD outcomes trials.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nPhase II evidence base substantial; Phase III in progress. Mechanistic case well-established for triple agonist. Cardiovascular and long-term safety profiles not yet fully characterized due to investigational status. Highest reported weight loss magnitude in any obesity pharmacotherapy trial to date.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational Phase II evidence (Jastreboff 2023 NEJM); Phase III TRIUMPH ongoing; mechanistic case well-grounded; highest weight loss magnitude reported in obesity pharmacotherapy. Anecdote: substantial research peptide and TRT/wellness clinic use ahead of FDA approval; community familiarity with titration and HR monitoring patterns; subjective effects on weight and body composition often perceptible faster than semaglutide or tirzepatide. Decision frame: highest-magnitude obesity pharmacotherapy molecule in clinical development; triple agonist mechanism is mechanistically distinctive; investigational status warrants honest risk acknowledgment; cardiovascular monitoring (HR, ECG) is the principal retatrutide-specific safety consideration alongside class GLP-1 RA AE patterns; mandatory protein and resistance training for lean mass preservation; pharmaceutical approval anticipated based on Phase II evidence but timeline contingent on Phase III completion.",
