    notes:
      "## What This Blend Is — And Isn't\n\nGLP-3 R+C is a **research peptide community blend product** combining retatrutide and cagrilintide in approximately 4:1 ratio. It is not a pharmaceutical pipeline product — neither Eli Lilly (retatrutide developer) nor Novo Nordisk (cagrilintide developer) has a corresponding development program. The blend exists in research peptide vendor formats as a single-injection convenience option for users running a retatrutide + cagrilintide combination ahead of any pharmaceutical approval.\n\n**Mechanistic logic:** the blend captures the highest-magnitude weight loss potential of any incretin pharmacology (retatrutide's triple GLP-1/GIP/GCG agonism) and adds the distinct amylin pathway via cagrilintide for additive or synergistic appetite suppression. The combination concept parallels Novo's CagriSema pharmaceutical strategy but substitutes a more potent incretin component.\n\n**What the blend is not:** equivalent to CagriSema. CagriSema is cagrilintide + semaglutide (1:1 ratio, ~2.4mg + ~2.4mg in Phase III). The retatrutide + cagrilintide combination is mechanistically distinct (triple agonist vs single agonist incretin component) and dosed differently (4:1 ratio reflecting retatrutide's higher therapeutic dose range).\n\n## Component-Equivalent Dosing — The Critical Practical Consideration\n\nThe principal user-facing risk in blend products is **dosing by total blend weight rather than component-equivalent doses**. Example calculation for a 10mg retatrutide + 2.5mg cagrilintide vial:\n\n- Total blend mass: 12.5mg\n- Reconstitute with 2.5mL bacteriostatic water → 5mg/mL total blend (4mg/mL retatrutide + 1mg/mL cagrilintide)\n- 0.5mL injection delivers: 2mg retatrutide + 0.5mg cagrilintide\n- 1.0mL injection delivers: 4mg retatrutide + 1mg cagrilintide\n- 1.25mL injection delivers: 5mg retatrutide + 1.25mg cagrilintide\n\n**Dose target by component, not by blend total.** Refer to individual retatrutide and cagrilintide tiles for component-specific dose ranges and titration guidance. The blend is convenient as a single-injection delivery vehicle but does not change the underlying component pharmacology.\n\n## When Blend vs Separate Component Injections\n\n**Blend advantages:**\n- Single weekly injection vs two separate injections\n- Fixed component ratio simplifies dose calculation once initial math is done\n- Lower per-dose injection burden\n\n**Separate component advantages:**\n- Independent titration of each component (useful when AE profiles of one component require dose adjustment without affecting the other)\n- Independent cessation of one component if needed (e.g., pause cagrilintide while continuing retatrutide)\n- Verification of each component's dose accuracy independently\n- Pharmaceutical-grade product availability (when retatrutide and/or cagrilintide reach FDA approval, separate components will be available pharmaceutically while blend products remain research peptide market only)\n\n**Practical recommendation:** users new to either component should run separate components first to characterize individual tolerability and AE profile, then transition to blend convenience after establishing stable component-equivalent doses and confirming the blend product matches expected component effects.\n\n## Combined AE Profile Considerations\n\nGI tolerability burden from combined gastric emptying delay (both retatrutide and cagrilintide arms) is amplified vs either monotherapy. Slower titration than either component alone is reasonable. Heart rate monitoring per retatrutide GCGR arm is unchanged in the blend context. Anesthesia / surgical aspiration considerations are amplified by combined gastric emptying delay — extended pre-procedural fasting beyond GLP-1 RA class guidance is reasonable.\n\n## Lean Mass Preservation — Class Considerations Apply\n\nBoth component arms drive weight loss; lean mass preservation considerations are identical to GLP-1 RA class — protein 1.6-2.2g/kg target body weight, resistance training, creatine, optional GH-axis support.\n\n## Synergies\n**GH-axis peptides** for lean mass preservation. **BPC-157** for GI healing. **Comprehensive nutrition**. **Resistance training**. The blend itself represents a synergy product — combining two component compounds for combined effect.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nNo blend-specific clinical trial evidence — the blend is not pharmaceutical pipeline. Component evidence is substantial (retatrutide Phase II / Phase III TRIUMPH; cagrilintide Phase II / Phase III REDEFINE). The combination effect is theoretical based on component mechanisms; no head-to-head comparison vs retatrutide monotherapy or vs CagriSema has been published.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: component evidence substantial via individual tiles; combination effect theoretical based on mechanism; no blend-specific RCT data. Anecdote: research peptide community use established; reported subjective effects on appetite and weight loss often greater than retatrutide monotherapy at equivalent retatrutide-equivalent doses; user community typically targets retatrutide-equivalent dosing with cagrilintide scaling proportionally to vial ratio. Decision frame: research peptide community blend product combining two investigational compounds; mechanistic rationale parallels CagriSema pharmaceutical strategy with substitution of triple agonist for single agonist incretin; component-equivalent dose calculation is essential; combined AE profile and monitoring considerations apply; pharmaceutical pipeline alternative is CagriSema (anticipated post-FDA approval) but the mechanism is not exactly equivalent.",
