    notes:
      "## NNMT Inhibition — The Mechanism Rationale\n\n5-Amino-1MQ is a small-molecule inhibitor of NNMT (nicotinamide N-methyltransferase), an enzyme that consumes both SAM (the universal methyl donor) and nicotinamide (a NAD+ precursor) while producing 1-methylnicotinamide (MNA) as a metabolic dead-end product. NNMT is highly expressed in adipose tissue with substantial elevation in obesity — and NNMT knockout mice are resistant to diet-induced obesity, providing mechanistic foundation for inhibiting NNMT as a body composition intervention.\n\nThe enzyme functions at an interesting metabolic crossroad:\n- **Consumes SAM** (depleting cellular methylation capacity)\n- **Consumes nicotinamide** (reducing NAD+ salvage substrate)\n- **Produces MNA** (a metabolic dead-end with limited downstream utility)\n\nInhibiting NNMT therefore preserves both SAM and nicotinamide, supporting both methylation capacity and NAD+ levels. The dual effect is the mechanistic case for NNMT inhibition as a metabolic-optimization intervention — distinct from NAD+ precursor supplementation alone (which only addresses the NAD+ side) and distinct from methyl donor supplementation alone (which only addresses the methylation side).\n\n## Distinct Mechanism — The Stacking Rationale\n\n5-Amino-1MQ's mechanism is non-overlapping with incretin pharmacology, GH peptides, melanocortin compounds, or amylin analogs. The non-overlapping mechanism is the rationale for stacking 5-Amino-1MQ with these other classes:\n\n**With GLP-1 RAs (semaglutide, tirzepatide, retatrutide):** GLP-1 RAs drive weight loss via central appetite mechanisms; 5-Amino-1MQ adds an adipose-tissue-specific NNMT inhibition mechanism that may support fat-specific loss vs lean-mass loss in the GLP-1-driven weight loss context.\n\n**With GH peptides (CJC-1295, ipamorelin, MOD-GRF, tesamorelin):** GH peptides drive lipolysis via GH-axis activation; 5-Amino-1MQ adds an adipose-tissue NNMT inhibition mechanism that may support the GH-axis-driven fat mobilization.\n\n**With NAD+ precursors (NMN, NR):** NAD+ precursors drive NAD+ salvage; 5-Amino-1MQ preserves the nicotinamide substrate by reducing NNMT consumption — possibly producing additive effect on cellular NAD+ levels.\n\n## Body Composition Application — The Community Use Case\n\nThe principal community application is body composition optimization — fat loss and lean mass preservation. 5-Amino-1MQ is rarely used as a standalone fat-loss intervention; it is most commonly layered into multi-mechanism stacks alongside GLP-1 RAs, GH peptides, or comprehensive metabolic optimization protocols.\n\n**Practical interpretation:** treat 5-Amino-1MQ as a layered adjunct rather than a primary fat-loss intervention. The mechanistic case is plausible; the clinical evidence is preclinical with limited human data. Community subjective reports suggest perceptible body composition effects when stacked with other interventions but the individual contribution is difficult to isolate without controlled comparison.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n50mg oral daily × 1-2 weeks (tolerance), then 100-150mg oral daily × 8-12 weeks. Track body composition (DEXA or BIA) and standard metabolic markers at start and end of protocol.\n\n## Stacked Protocol Examples\n\n**With GLP-1 RAs (community standard for fat loss):**\n- 5-Amino-1MQ 100-150mg oral daily\n- Semaglutide / tirzepatide / retatrutide per individual tile dosing\n- Mandatory protein 1.6-2.2g/kg target body weight + resistance training\n- 12-16 week protocol\n\n**With GH peptides (community use for body composition):**\n- 5-Amino-1MQ 100-150mg oral daily\n- CJC-1295 No-DAC + Ipamorelin pre-sleep dosing per GH peptide tiles\n- Comprehensive resistance training and nutrition foundation\n- 8-12 week protocol\n\n**Comprehensive metabolic optimization stack:**\n- 5-Amino-1MQ 100-150mg oral daily\n- NAD+ precursor (NMN 500mg-1g daily, or NR 300-600mg daily)\n- Comprehensive methylation support (B-complex methylated, betaine if appropriate)\n- Lifestyle foundation: sleep, stress management, exercise, time-restricted eating as appropriate\n\n## Synergies\n**GLP-1 RAs:** non-overlapping mechanism for fat-loss stacking. **GH peptides:** complementary adipose-tissue effects. **NAD+ precursors:** additive effects on cellular NAD+. **Comprehensive nutrition:** elevated protein, adequate methyl-relevant nutrients (folate, B12, betaine, choline). **Resistance training**.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nKraus et al. 2014 (NNMT mechanism foundational publication). Sauve laboratory body of work at Weill Cornell. Animal model evidence base substantial; human clinical trial evidence essentially absent.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized at the enzyme and cell biology level. Animal model evidence base substantial for adipose tissue effects, body composition, and muscle stem cell function. Human clinical trial evidence essentially absent. Long-term safety profile not characterized due to lack of pharmaceutical development.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic case (NNMT enzyme biology); substantial animal model evidence; human clinical evidence essentially absent; no pharmaceutical development pipeline. Anecdote: research peptide / longevity supplement community use established; reported subjective effects on body composition and energy when stacked with other metabolic interventions; individual contribution difficult to isolate. Decision frame: small molecule with distinct NNMT-inhibition mechanism providing non-overlapping pathway in multi-mechanism metabolic stacks; mechanism well-characterized but clinical evidence base preclinical with limited human data; appropriate as a layered adjunct in fat-loss / body composition protocols rather than as a primary intervention; oral bioavailability is the practical advantage vs injection-route compounds; pairs naturally with GLP-1 RAs, GH peptides, and comprehensive metabolic optimization stacks.",
